# Fluff Date: 2026-02-21 18:07:19
overview:<p>The Dart is a twenty-five-ton light BattleMech introduced in 3051 by Coventry Metal Works in response to a Federated Commonwealth request for ammunition-independent designs. Conceived as a fast raider and reconnaissance platform, the Dart was engineered to operate deep behind enemy lines without reliance on vulnerable supply chains. The design represented Coventry Metal Works' bid to secure a place among the Commonwealth's primary military suppliers, leveraging existing production infrastructure to keep costs low while meeting the demanding specifications of the Clan Invasion era. Fielding an all-energy weapons suite and capable of speeds exceeding one hundred fifty kilometers per hour, the Dart quickly proved its worth in Periphery patrols and border skirmishes, earning a lasting place in Lyran and Federated Suns arsenals that has endured well into the thirty-second century.</p>
capabilities:<p>The Dart's primary asset is its exceptional speed, powered by a VOX 225 fusion engine that propels the twenty-five-ton chassis to a top speed of one hundred fifty-one kilometers per hour. This makes the Dart one of the fastest BattleMechs in its weight class, capable of outrunning most threats it cannot outfight. The design philosophy centers entirely on self-sufficiency and sustained independent operations, with no ammunition dependencies to limit its patrol endurance.</p><p>Armament consists of three Magna 200P small pulse lasers, providing highly accurate short-range firepower well-suited to strafing attacks against softer targets. While the damage output is modest against heavier opponents, the pulse lasers' accuracy allows the Dart to make the most of its fleeting firing windows during high-speed passes. Operating in swarms or alongside other fast light units, Darts can overwhelm slower opponents through sheer volume of attacks from multiple vectors.</p><p>The Dart's greatest vulnerability is its armor protection, with only three and a half tons of Lexington Limited plating covering the chassis. A single well-placed volley from a medium-weight opponent can cripple the design, making pilot skill and situational awareness critical survival factors. The extended torso twist capability provides some additional defensive flexibility, allowing MechWarriors to spread incoming damage more effectively during withdrawal maneuvers.</p>
deployment:<p>This variant replaces the three small pulse lasers with three medium lasers, significantly extending the variant's effective engagement range and increasing its damage potential per volley. This modification directly addressed field commanders' complaints that the base model's short-range armament forced MechWarriors into dangerously close engagements against targets that could easily destroy the lightly armored chassis. While sacrificing the pulse lasers' enhanced accuracy, the medium lasers allow this variant to engage targets at meaningful standoff distances while maintaining the design's hallmark ammunition independence. Originally fielded as a field refit beginning around 3053, Coventry Metal Works subsequently adopted the configuration as a factory-direct production option.</p>
history:<p>The Dart debuted during the opening years of the Clan Invasion, with the first production models seeing action in Periphery regions where they were put through their paces in relative secrecy, hunting pirates and conducting long-range patrols far from the main front lines. After the Battle of Tukayyid in 3052, the bulk of Coventry's early production runs were allocated to AFFC units stationed along the Clan border, where the Dart served as a fast raider and screening element throughout the 3050s and into the early 3060s.</p><p>Intelligence analysts believe that during this period, invading Clans captured several Darts and traded them among themselves as examples of inferior Inner Sphere technology. These captured machines were retained primarily as garrison assets, a theory supported by encounters with Darts bearing Smoke Jaguar colors during the liberation of Huntress, despite no confirmed losses to that Clan during the post-Tukayyid era.</p><p>The FedCom Civil War saw Darts deployed on both sides of the conflict, with Loyalist and Allied units alike making use of the design's speed for reconnaissance and fast-response operations. Engagements along the Lyran-Davion border frequently featured Darts in screening roles, where their speed proved invaluable for maintaining contact with enemy formations and relaying targeting data to heavier elements.</p><p>Coventry Metal Works has continued to produce the Dart and its variants throughout the Jihad and into the Dark Age, with the design remaining a staple of Lyran Commonwealth armed forces. The introduction of the DRT-6T during the Jihad expanded the Dart's tactical envelope into a sniper and harassment role, ensuring the chassis remained relevant against increasingly sophisticated opponents. Production has remained active at the Coventry facility under consistent Lyran ownership, providing a steady supply of these light raiders to frontline and garrison units across the Commonwealth.</p>
